Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives.
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have likened the Japanese earthquakes, tsunamis and nuclear catastrophe to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates significant profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
However, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their reappearance begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with normally harmless design defects, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
In terms of financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivatives and repos markets, has impaired the ability of major financial institutions to honour their debts.
Although the underlying risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, an overinvestment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and bad luck have ensured that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a credit freeze on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand the risks and design flaws of Fukushima quite well.
One cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives products that have sent the global economy reeling.
At Fukushima, the teams of workers bravely try to stop the leaks of radiation.
On the other hand, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are in the process of recreating similar derivative products and financial structures, right over the same active errors.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first one promises to provide euros by June 1, and the second one promises to provide yen.
If a currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Rests are financial transactions.
Financial institutions sell assets, such as government bonds or mortgage debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets, typically the next day (hence the name "repo", an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or buy back).
The problem is that the cash coming from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheet of the most important financial institutions, which implies that simple financial shocks can affect them strongly.
Certain institutions may then be deprived of repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, such as Bear Stearns.
Taken individually, transactions on derivative or repo products are not particularly objectionable.
Each transfers the risk in a legitimate manner separately to those who are better equipped to bear it, or allows financial participation.
However, when they are used excessively by systemic institutions that are vital, they can blow up the financial system due to its design flaws.
Even today, nearly 70% of the debt of the main American financial companies consists of very short-term loans, such as payables due tomorrow.
In the United States, primary design flaws are found in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and most repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors holding derivative or repo contracts with financially weakened financial institutions may seize the company's assets before - and at the expense of - its normal creditors. This way, they can decide its fate, whereas, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns and others during the financial crisis.
Even worse, because derivatives and repos investors end up at the front of the queue for redemptions in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be reimbursed, anyway.
Of course, someone must be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions of actors in derivatives and repo products place them at the forefront in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect others to have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in the line is too often the US government, as guarantor of 'too-big-to-fail' financial institutions (too big to be allowed to fail). However, the government is ill-placed to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
He is not financially agile; he often sticks to the regulated market; and when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to solve this defect in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer via the Dodd Frank bill.
But he did not catch it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit-event derivatives) were not given favored treatment, they would behave differently.
Above all, they would insist more often that their counterparts be capitalized appropriately.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalizations when it essentially came to American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives the risks of the Fukushima type differently and the risks associated with derivatives.
Many people fear the nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must face security concerns.
But derivatives and repos markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to convey in the media and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and scorn, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Concerning risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami risks using passive cooling systems.
Today it is considered feasible to predict nuclear power plants capable of keeping cool fuel rods even in the event of a total power outage.
On the other hand, few significant progress have been made so far to prevent the damage that prioritizing derivatives and repo in case of insolvency could cause during a new crisis of the financial system.
New rules are being developed, which require end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect themselves from unexpected changes in oil prices) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline for major financial institutions.
It all seems to be happening as if we are reacting to Fukushima by controlling emissions better in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully assign to derivatives investors and rest the risk related to their decisions when they conduct transactions with systemically critical financial institutions.
Instead, we only survived the 2008 financial tsunami to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial shortcomings and according to the same faulty design.
